{
  "doc_id": "57036",
  "text": "The assumption that the relationship between leaf area and AS is linear [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] is not applicable to our data. This is likely due to variations in AL : AS d.b.h. that are related to crown conditions [CITATION_3] , crown base height [CITATION_4] , tree age (our study), management and other modifications associated with differing physiological responses to altered environmental conditions [CITATION_5] . While the infl uence of crown depth on altering AL : AS d.b.h. can be overcome by assessing FB as a function of AS at crown height (AS HZ ), these measurements are not always readily available and, therefore, cannot be used to estimate FB from standard inventory data. AS HZ can be estimated using a TF, but the TF should be modifi ed to account for small trees where the crown height is below 1.3 m (AS HZ > AS d.b.h. , [CITATION_6] . Also, there was still considerable variation in AL : AS HZ across sites of different ages, suggesting that interspecifi c variation should not be ignored for modelling purposes. [CITATION_7] also warned that ignoring similar within-stand variation would substantially bias leaf area and LAI estimates. Speculation as to the causes for variations in AL : AS HZ includes climate-and site-related factors [CITATION_8] , tree vigour, alterations in stem hydraulic conductance [CITATION_9] , the extent of AS taper and variations in crown-free stem length [CITATION_10] .",
